developerResponse: {'reviewId': 'fc60f90a-e73b-42a1-be87-4dfd84f62438', 'userName': 'A Google user', 'userImage': 'https://play-lh.googleusercontent.com/EGemoI2NTXmTsBVtJqk8jxF9rh8ApRWfsIMQSt2uE4OcpQqbFu7f7NbTK05lx80nuSijCz7sc3a277R67g', 'content': "I normally love the apps from RV, but as a teacher I'm passing on this one. The letter sounds are not helpful to students learning to sound out spellings. For instance, the sound for letter C in the app is 'cuh', and T is 'tuh'. review: I normally love the apps from RV, but as a teacher I'm passing on this one. The letter sounds are not helpful to students learning to sound out spellings. For instance, the sound for letter C in the app is 'cuh', and T is 'tuh'. When you attempt to put the sounds together into the word cat, the sounds put together sound like 'cuh-a-tuh'. Kids, especially ones who struggle with reading or speech, will only be more confused with the extra vowel sounds tacked onto many consonant sounds in this app.

developerResponse: {'reviewId': 'e85c1977-961e-44ff-9ec7-cd75a954e41b', 'userName': 'A Google user', 'userImage': 'https://play-lh.googleusercontent.com/EGemoI2NTXmTsBVtJqk8jxF9rh8ApRWfsIMQSt2uE4OcpQqbFu7f7NbTK05lx80nuSijCz7sc3a277R67g', 'content': 'It\'s such a cute app, and I use your company\'s apps all the time for my younger students, but I have to speak over the voice because most of the phonemes are mispronounced. For example \'r\' should make an "er" sound not "ruh" etc. Then soft \'g\' in the word "gem" is sounded out with hard \'g\'. Long vowels are mispronounced as short, and the silent \'e\' shouldn\'t be pronounced at all. You should pair the vowel with the \'e\' producing a long sound. Same goes for \'r\' controlled words like "car".', 'score': 3, 'thumbsUpCount': 104, 'reviewCreatedVersion': '1.1.8', 'at': datetime.datetime(2019, 4, 26, 12, 49, 49), 'replyContent': None, 'repliedAt': None, 'appVersion': '1.1.8'}
review: It's such a cute app, and I use your company's apps all the time for my younger students, but I have to speak over the voice because most of the phonemes are mispronounced. For example 'r' should make an "er" sound not "ruh" etc. Then soft 'g' in the word "gem" is sounded out with hard 'g'. Long vowels are mispronounced as short, and the silent 'e' shouldn't be pronounced at all. You should pair the vowel with the 'e' producing a long sound. Same goes for 'r' controlled words like "car".

developerResponse:
{'reviewId': '0c033bcf-7832-4df3-9feb-0e34c3de7274', 'userName': 'A Google user', 'userImage': 'https://play-lh.googleusercontent.com/EGemoI2NTXmTsBVtJqk8jxF9rh8ApRWfsIMQSt2uE4OcpQqbFu7f7NbTK05lx80nuSijCz7sc3a277R67g', 'content': "Nice game, very colorful, but I've always taught my children from a young 
age to read. My oldest started at 8 months, and was actively reading by 18 
months. This program didn't take into account that capital letters only 
come at the beginning of sentences, and children see capital letters less 
than lower case. Children should start out with lower case letters and then 
capital letters will be understood at a later age after reading becomes 
easier. Adults seem to neglect this.", 'score': 3, 'thumbsUpCount': 140, 'reviewCreatedVersion': '1.1.2', 'at': datetime.datetime(2018, 5, 2, 16, 40, 42), 'replyContent': None, 'repliedAt': None, 'appVersion': '1.1.2'}
review:
Nice game, very colorful, but I've always taught my children from a young 
age to read. My oldest started at 8 months, and was actively reading by 18 
months. This program didn't take into account that capital letters only 
come at the beginning of sentences, and children see capital letters less 
than lower case. Children should start out with lower case letters and then 
capital letters will be understood at a later age after reading becomes 
easier. Adults seem to neglect this.

review: The game is very interactive and easy to use. My 3yr old seems to be liking it, and learning the phonics quickly and in the right way. Still early days though, so let's hope it continues to capture his interest.  My only suggestion would be that there should be background music volume controller so we can keep it on but at a lower volume. This will help understand the phonic sounds a bit clearer, as they become slightly inaudible with the Lloyd background music.

review: Overall the concept is cool, however the gameplay is very rigid. For each word, it repeats it multiple times and forces you to sit through the full sequence every time. That's fine at first, but learning happens through repetition, so once your kid starts learning they really need the ability to skip the boring parts. Taking away their control really kills the interactivity.
